{"id":"2207.09125","submitter":"Stefano Pinton Mr","authors":"Antonino De Martino and Stefano Pinton","title":"A polyanalytic functional calculus of order 2 on the S-spectrum","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:2205.08162","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Fueter theorem provides a two step procedure to build an axially\nmonogenic function, i.e. a null-solutions of the Cauchy-Riemann operator in $\n\\mathbb{R}^4$, denoted by $ \\mathcal{D}$. In the first step a holomorphic\nfunction is extended to a slice hyperholomorphic function, by means of the\nso-called slice operator. In the second step a monogenic function is built by\napplying the Laplace operator in four real variables ($\\Delta$) to the slice\nhyperholomorphic function. In this paper we use the factorization of the\nLaplace operator, i.e. $\\Delta= \\mathcal{\\overline{D}} \\mathcal{D}$ to split\nthe previous procedure. From this splitting we get a class of functions that\nlies between the set of slice hyperholomorphic functions and the set of axially\nmonogenic functions: the set of axially polyanalytic functions of order 2, i.e.\nnull-solutions of $ \\mathcal{D}^2$. We show an integral representation formula\nfor this kind of functions. The formula obtained is fundamental to define the\nassociated functional calculus on the $S$-spectrum. As far as the authors know,\nthis is the first time that a monogenic polyanalytic functional calculus has\nbeen taken into consideration.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 19 Jul 2022 08:43:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-20"}
